47
00:04:23,910 --> 00:04:34,873
So our individual shelter alone services 16 people and our family shelter holds five families at a time, a maximum of 20 people.

48
00:04:36,713 --> 00:04:47,436
At a given time, like I did street outreach today and I would say we probably saw 15 people out in encampment and then probably another maybe five to ten people sitting in Davis Square.

49
00:04:48,886 --> 00:04:58,851
Separate from that, we also provide what's called permanent supportive housing, which is when we go out and we rent apartments, take people out of homelessness and put them in those apartments.

50
00:04:59,571 --> 00:05:04,614
So through that program, we lease up over 60 units and house probably over 100 people.

51
00:05:04,634 --> 00:05:05,394
That's amazing.

52
00:05:05,474 --> 00:05:12,978
And then, yeah, we also have our food pantry that on an average month, we see probably 300 to 400 people.

53
00:05:13,738 --> 00:05:16,439
Currently, we're definitely seeing that number kind of double.

54
00:05:18,326 --> 00:05:21,950
So it really all depends on the program as far as how many people we see.

55
00:05:22,611 --> 00:05:22,851
Yeah.

56
00:05:23,192 --> 00:05:24,413
And where does your funding come from?

57
00:05:26,395 --> 00:05:29,038
Oh, kind of everywhere, honestly.

58
00:05:29,879 --> 00:05:33,884
Our family shelter is primarily funded through DHCD.

59
00:05:34,385 --> 00:05:38,950
The state, our adult shelter has city funding, has state funding.

60
00:05:39,441 --> 00:05:40,402
the federal government.

61
00:05:40,762 --> 00:05:44,504
A lot of our homelessness prevention comes from the city of Somerville.

62
00:05:45,465 --> 00:05:49,808
We just kind of pieced together a lot of different funding sources to make sure we can stay open.

63
00:05:50,308 --> 00:05:51,909
And a lot of fundraising, that's for sure.

64
00:05:51,949 --> 00:05:59,274
We just did an online campaign where we raised, to the best of my knowledge, I think over $100,000, which was huge for us.

65
00:05:59,314 --> 00:06:01,956
Yeah, that's amazing.

66
00:06:02,837 --> 00:06:07,780
Can you talk about how COVID-19 is affecting the people that you're helping?

67
00:06:10,413 --> 00:06:14,856
You know, it's stressful, much like everybody else.

68
00:06:15,417 --> 00:06:18,539
And again, it kind of divides up into the different sections.

69
00:06:18,639 --> 00:06:23,763
Like our permanent supportive housing program, their services are now remote.

70
00:06:24,464 --> 00:06:35,212
And it's really hard to provide case management to an 18-year-old in recovery and living on their own for the first time when it's just a phone call.

71
00:06:36,166 --> 00:06:48,569
Or our shelter, now we're only, we've capped it at 13 right now, hoping to move out some more people, that way we can lower the number even more, because social distancing just does not exist in a homeless shelter.

72
00:06:49,429 --> 00:06:50,129
It's real hard.

73
00:06:51,269 --> 00:06:57,410
Our family shelter, the kids aren't in school, so we're trying to engage them, we're trying to educate them.

74
00:06:58,090 --> 00:07:02,671
All of a sudden, the direct care workers are now teachers, just as much as parents are.

75
00:07:07,070 --> 00:07:08,831
Yeah, it's definitely hard.

76
00:07:08,851 --> 00:07:16,296
I think we're all tired, and we'll be grateful when it's over, but we're showing up every day.

77
00:07:16,736 --> 00:07:18,317
Our services remain open.

78
00:07:19,278 --> 00:07:22,199
We're still street outreaching, which is great.

79
00:07:22,800 --> 00:07:26,142
We have our masks on, we have our gloves on when we go out there, but

80
00:07:27,200 --> 00:07:39,888
You know, today when I was in the woods, a lot of people that typically make their money off of hand handling aren't getting money because people aren't going to work or people are afraid to stick their hand out the car window and give money.

81
00:07:40,009 --> 00:07:44,532
So people now are starving in the woods because they don't have any money to buy food.

82
00:07:45,112 --> 00:07:48,514
So when we go out there, it is constantly like, do you have food today?

83
00:07:48,534 --> 00:07:49,515
Do you have water?

84
00:07:49,715 --> 00:07:51,156
You know, those basic needs that

85
00:07:51,979 --> 00:07:57,000
normally aren't as dire, really are dire at this point.

86
00:07:57,420 --> 00:08:05,001
So things that I never thought kind of would have come up, like money from panhandling, but we're definitely seeing a lot of it.

87
00:08:05,021 --> 00:08:06,502
Wow.

88
00:08:08,422 --> 00:08:13,963
What do you think is the best way for people to be able to help out?

89
00:08:14,243 --> 00:08:16,363
Where can they donate?

90
00:08:16,643 --> 00:08:17,584
Can they volunteer?

91
00:08:17,604 --> 00:08:19,704
Are there other ways that they can help?

92
00:08:21,274 --> 00:08:27,357
Yeah, I know our food pantry is taking volunteers because they are getting absolutely swamped.

93
00:08:27,717 --> 00:08:32,699
I think it was the month of March, typically we see 300 people and it was over 800 people.

94
00:08:34,120 --> 00:08:39,562
You know, surrounding cities that have had to close their food pantries, people are now coming to Somerville.

95
00:08:40,043 --> 00:08:40,703
That typically

96
00:08:41,373 --> 00:08:44,735
You know, we don't service, but we're not going to turn somebody away for food.

97
00:08:45,356 --> 00:08:51,740
So we are, you know, really looking for people to donate food to Project Soup, our food pantry.

98
00:08:51,760 --> 00:08:58,085
They can go, they can help sort cans because we're just handing out bags of food at this point.

99
00:08:58,385 --> 00:09:00,026
So we need to pack those bags.

100
00:09:01,022 --> 00:09:03,903
As well as, you know, you can always go on the website and donate money.

101
00:09:03,923 --> 00:09:09,484
Honestly, we're operating our shelter 24-7 right now, and that's not something we have funding for.

102
00:09:09,504 --> 00:09:16,326
Typically, our shelter's only open 16 hours a day, and since the beginning of March, we've been open 24-7.

103
00:09:16,406 --> 00:09:19,487
So, that's something that, you know, we need to find funding for.

104
00:09:19,507 --> 00:09:23,348
And that's one way the community could help, that's for sure.

105
00:09:24,308 --> 00:09:24,948
Absolutely.

106
00:09:26,764 --> 00:09:32,807
Do you have any final thoughts, anything else that you want people to know about what's happening?

107
00:09:33,288 --> 00:09:54,901
Oh, you know, I heard on WBUR there was a segment on homeless shelters, and all I remember is hearing that they had gotten enough tests to test an entire homeless shelter, like every single person in the shelter, and that some crazy high percentage of them

108
00:09:56,370 --> 00:09:57,331
One in three.

109
00:09:57,431 --> 00:10:01,354
Yeah, that's what I remember, but I didn't want to quote it because it seems so high.

110
00:10:01,734 --> 00:10:06,498
But a lot of them were asymptomatic and they didn't show signs of the disease.

111
00:10:06,918 --> 00:10:08,840
What do you think that that means?

112
00:10:10,921 --> 00:10:17,907
You know, I think it's hard because we've really heard when it comes to, you know, the shelters, we need three things.

113
00:10:17,987 --> 00:10:21,469
We need depopulation, we need quarantine, and we need isolation.

114
00:10:21,489 --> 00:10:21,549
And

115
00:10:24,462 --> 00:10:32,584
I feel like this is always an issue with homelessness is, is it going to be a state response, is it going to be a regional response, a federal response, or a local response?

116
00:10:32,744 --> 00:10:35,484
And I've never seen that more present than I do right now.

117
00:10:35,564 --> 00:10:36,945
You know, how are we going to respond?

118
00:10:37,005 --> 00:10:38,005
Is it going to be the city?

119
00:10:38,065 --> 00:10:39,025
Is it going to be the state?

120
00:10:39,085 --> 00:10:40,105
Is it going to be regional?

121
00:10:41,425 --> 00:10:47,607
And so as we kind of sort that out, you know, things start, people get symptomatic, people get sick.

122
00:10:49,785 --> 00:10:51,006
It hit Boston hard.

123
00:10:51,186 --> 00:10:53,727
It hit the Boston shelters really hard, one in three.

124
00:10:54,367 --> 00:10:56,488
And now it's starting to make its way over the river.

125
00:10:56,888 --> 00:10:59,770
It's going to hit Cambridge, and then it's going to slowly progress.

126
00:11:00,670 --> 00:11:14,297
So the more we can do to get ahead of it and depopulate our shelters and set up those quarantine sites is going to really make the difference from Boston to the city of Somerville and Medford and the surrounding areas.

127
00:11:15,229 --> 00:11:15,929
Yeah, absolutely.

128
00:11:15,969 --> 00:11:21,411
And so it sounds like the program that you have where you actually house people is the safest for them.

129
00:11:22,851 --> 00:11:23,751
Correct.

130
00:11:23,851 --> 00:11:27,492
In addition to being obviously the best for them.

131
00:11:27,732 --> 00:11:31,573
When you can house people and they can have their own home, it's clearly better for many reasons.

132
00:11:31,713 --> 00:11:34,314
But here in COVID-19, it's even more crucial.

133
00:11:35,617 --> 00:11:36,017
Exactly.

134
00:11:36,057 --> 00:11:45,185
It's really showing kind of the holes in the system and what really will make the difference for homelessness in the future, which in reality will always be housing.

135
00:11:45,385 --> 00:11:48,408
It will always be what makes the difference for someone experiencing homelessness.

136
00:11:51,145 --> 00:11:52,525
Well, thank you so much.

137
00:11:53,726 --> 00:12:01,848
The work you guys do is totally amazing, and I don't envy you the amount of work that you have to do these days.

138
00:12:03,148 --> 00:12:07,949
So, you know, we will be encouraging people to help you out, to volunteer and donate.

139
00:12:07,969 --> 00:12:10,030
Thank you so much.

140
00:12:10,170 --> 00:12:14,831
Yeah, it's really good to have an update, and stay safe.

141
00:12:16,311 --> 00:12:17,351
Do personal care.

142
00:12:17,371 --> 00:12:17,931
Thank you.

143
00:12:18,412 --> 00:12:19,692
Everything that you need to do.

144
00:12:21,452 --> 00:12:22,153
And thank you so much.

145
00:12:22,173 --> 00:12:23,913
Thank you.

146
00:12:23,953 --> 00:12:24,534
I appreciate it.

147
00:12:24,774 --> 00:12:26,074
Yeah.

148
00:12:26,274 --> 00:12:36,798
I'm going to go ahead and bring on David Tissell from the Somerville Community Corporation.

149
00:12:36,838 --> 00:12:40,900
Let me just switch the titles here.

150
00:12:40,920 --> 00:12:41,300
Here he is.

151
00:12:41,320 --> 00:12:43,421
Hey, we've got you on.

152
00:12:43,441 --> 00:12:43,481
Hi.

153
00:12:43,501 --> 00:12:43,661
Hey.

154
00:12:43,961 --> 00:12:44,781
Hi, Anna.

155
00:12:47,830 --> 00:12:49,091
Thanks for being on.

156
00:12:49,111 --> 00:13:00,741
I would love to hear a little bit about what the Somerville Community Corporation does and your role specifically.

157
00:13:00,761 --> 00:13:03,783
Sure.

158
00:13:03,803 --> 00:13:12,211
So the Somerville Community Corporation or SCC is a nonprofit community development corporation for the city of Somerville.

159
00:13:13,228 --> 00:13:20,731
Our main areas of work are building and owning and operating affordable housing.

160
00:13:21,312 --> 00:13:26,854
We have about 275 units throughout the city scattered around in different buildings.

161
00:13:27,274 --> 00:13:35,658
We also have a team of people that helps Somerville and other nearby area residents get jobs in the community.

162
00:13:35,678 --> 00:13:40,660
And we also do community organizing for policies that

163
00:13:41,258 --> 00:13:44,320
support economic justice locally and in the state.

164
00:13:45,381 --> 00:13:51,966
So my work is on the affordable housing side with my supervisor, Scott.

165
00:13:53,047 --> 00:14:10,541
I manage a program called 100 Homes where we purchase buildings in Somerville and convert them to affordable housing using subsidy from the city of Somerville, sometimes also from state and federal, but mostly from the city, and then also like private mortgages

166
00:14:13,011 --> 00:14:19,814
And so in this program, we have right now 85 units in the 100 homes program.

167
00:14:20,235 --> 00:14:20,975
You're getting close.

168
00:14:21,215 --> 00:14:31,480
And it differs from sort of traditional affordable housing development in that it's the already existing structures that become affordable rather than creating a new building.

169
00:14:32,721 --> 00:14:34,482
Yeah, that's very important.

170
00:14:36,106 --> 00:14:43,628
I mean, it seems like there's only a certain amount of new construction you can do in the densest city in the whole of New England.

171
00:14:44,748 --> 00:14:57,791
Right, and it's really expensive now to buy anything in Somerville, but especially to purchase land, hold it, try to get your zoning, try to get in line for tax credits and everything to do the traditional development is really hard now.

172
00:14:57,811 --> 00:15:00,212
We still are doing that and trying to do that.

173
00:15:00,332 --> 00:15:03,933
But in addition, we decided that based on

174
00:15:04,651 --> 00:15:11,397
just the community and the market that we're in, that this was a way to further our mission at this time through purchasing buildings.

175
00:15:11,777 --> 00:15:13,619
Yeah, that is great.

176
00:15:14,279 --> 00:15:22,967
So I'd love to hear how COVID-19 is affecting your organizing, is affecting your tenants, like what do you see happening?

177
00:15:24,728 --> 00:15:27,030
Yeah, so my, I know

178
00:15:29,124 --> 00:15:33,946
I guess the most about just on the landlord side, because once we buy these places, we own them.

179
00:15:35,447 --> 00:15:41,330
And definitely our rent collections are less than usual for this time of month.

180
00:15:41,830 --> 00:15:49,154
We've had a large number of tenants reach out to us that they've lost their jobs or that their hours have been cut.

181
00:15:49,934 --> 00:15:53,196
And a lot of them are trying to apply for unemployment.

182
00:15:55,105 --> 00:16:08,672
And our team of people that helps people get jobs is mostly focusing on helping people get unemployment now, because there aren't that many new jobs, except there's some at Be Fresh, I guess, and some other places where they're hiring more people.

183
00:16:11,013 --> 00:16:21,538
And we have a large number of tenants that are immigrants, and some of them have different statuses.

184
00:16:23,405 --> 00:16:37,129
immigration status, and so people that are undocumented typically can't utilize the same benefits that people that are residents or permanent residents or citizens can.

185
00:16:37,949 --> 00:16:49,112
So it's especially tough for some of those people, some of those tenants that we have that can't work now, so they're like zero income, so they can't pay their rent.

186
00:16:51,727 --> 00:16:59,030
You know, we are trying to help everyone to the extent we can, and there are some funds set up.

187
00:16:59,090 --> 00:17:06,212
For example, there's one, Cosecha has a fund, and also there's a new one that just is launched, I think, today.

188
00:17:06,892 --> 00:17:15,715
United Way and City of Somerville, with CAS, the Community Action Agency of Somerville, sort of came together and launched this fund for Somerville residents.

189
00:17:16,476 --> 00:17:19,677
So we're steering people towards those resources in addition to trying to help them

190
00:17:21,125 --> 00:17:35,212
get unemployment or there's also what's called RAFT, which is a state-funded, state of Massachusetts-funded rental arrears, rental assistance program.

191
00:17:35,252 --> 00:17:36,673
So we're helping people apply for that too.

192
00:17:37,013 --> 00:17:39,994
Is that something new to COVID-19 or is that something that existed before?

193
00:17:41,415 --> 00:17:44,977
It existed before, but it's been expanded because of COVID-19.

194
00:17:44,997 --> 00:17:45,117
Yeah.

195
00:17:46,571 --> 00:17:52,734
So can you talk just a little bit more about that in case there are people listening who might be interested in looking into that?

196
00:17:53,894 --> 00:18:02,978
Yeah, so RAFT is administered around Somerville by Metro Housing Boston, and the information is on their website.

197
00:18:03,958 --> 00:18:07,600
And basically, you can apply for arrears

198
00:18:09,345 --> 00:18:16,775
or up to $4,000 of budget, or it could be a mix of arrears and future budget.

199
00:18:17,395 --> 00:18:25,646
So like if you're behind, if your rent's like $2,000 and you're behind one month, you could apply for the month you're behind and next month.

200
00:18:29,222 --> 00:18:31,325
And you have to provide a lot of documentation.

201
00:18:31,345 --> 00:18:34,288
I'm not going to go over all of it, and I can't remember all of it.

202
00:18:34,688 --> 00:18:39,414
But if you look for RAFT in Metro Housing Boston, you'll see the application.

203
00:18:39,434 --> 00:18:47,443
You'll see what type of stuff you have to attach, like stuff about your income status and documentation of your income.

204
00:18:47,878 --> 00:18:49,219
Okay, good to know.

205
00:18:49,239 --> 00:19:01,003
You know, it's funny, shortly before this call, I happened to be talking to my mom who lives in California, and she was saying that Governor Gavin Newsom

206
00:19:03,150 --> 00:19:21,032
you know, had very recently given a speech or a talk where he was saying that 10% of Californians are undocumented and that these undocumented workers were the people growing the food, were the people

207
00:19:22,074 --> 00:19:36,903
delivering the food and other essentials, they were the people working in the grocery stores, that these are the essential workers, and that he was going to ensure that they had medical care, that they were all gonna get unemployment.

